Since nested classes and enums are rendered as dollar sign separated in Java, we cannot import specific subclasses into Python. We can import everything from a package (including nested classes & enums) but the dollar sign in their names is retained meaning they must be accessed via their name in a string. 

Here is an example

In Java:
```java
package MyPackage;

public class MyClass {
    public enum MyEnum {
        VALUE1("Val One"),
        VALUE2("Val Two");
        
        private String val;
        
        Test(String val){ this.val = val; }
    }
}
```

In Python:
```python
from MyPackage import *
print(str(globals()['MyClass$MyEnum'].VALUE1))  # prints "Val One"
```
Ideally it would be possible to do `from MyPackage.MyClass import MyEnum` but I have no idea if this is feasible in Python. Failing this, it might be useful to replace any dollar signs with an underscore.

